Question:
As shown in the figure. Show that a punctured tube from a bicycle tire can be turned inside out. (More precisely, this would be possible if the rubber from which the tube is made were elastic enough. In real life it is impossible to turn a punctured tube inside out.). Sort the figures to show this process. (Then we can change the position of the obtained figure so that its "inside" (shown in white) becomes its "outside" (the shaded side of the surface) and vice-versa, simply by moving it as a rigid body in space until the hoop 1 occupies the position of the hoop 2. Once this is done, the previous deformations performed in reverse order result in the tube being turned inside out as required.)

Options:
A: \(\,(2)\to(1)\to(3)\to(4)\,\)
B: \(\,(2)\to(3)\to(1)\to(4)\,\)
C: \(\,(1)\to(2)\to(3)\to(4)\,\)
D: \(\,(1)\to(3)\to(2)\to(4)\,\)
E: \(\,(3)\to(2)\to(1)\to(4)\,\)

message.content:
The punctured tube is first deformed by pulling the inner rim out to form the cross-shaped configuration (1).  
Then the rim is spread and bent to the more symmetric intermediate shape (2).  
Next, it is stretched further into the looped configuration (3).  
Finally, it is rearranged rigidly into the linked-hoops configuration (4).  

Answer:C
